<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="123">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. acrostacta" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acrostacta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="123">P. acrostacta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but can be differentiated primarily by the yellow face in males and larger basal spot in cell dm. Specimens were not available for study but photographs of both sexes have been examined: 2♂, 2♀, India: Rajasthan, Jodhpur District, 10 km SW Jodhpur, Machia Safari Pk, Malaise in dry wash 29.II-5.III.2008, 300 m, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="26" direction="north" minutes="18.60" orientation="latitude" precision="9" value="26.31">26°18.60'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate degrees="72" direction="east" minutes="58.71" orientation="longitude" precision="9" value="72.9785">72°58.71'E</geoCoordinate>
(in California Academy of Sciences, San Francisco, California, USA).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="123" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="123">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="123">This endemic Indian species is known only from Maharashtra and Rajasthan.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
